07284nam a22014535i 9780691245645DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912456457 a10.1515/97806912456452doi  a(DE-B1597)649970  a(OCoLC)1350093783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJA71b.S64647 2023 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a320.01223/eng/202211011 aSonenscher, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAfter Kant :bThe Romans, the Germans, and the Moderns in the History of Political Thought /cMichael Sonenscher. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (584 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Palingenesis, History, and Politics -- t3 The Coppet Group and the Liberty of the Moderns -- t4 Germaine de Staël and Modern Politics -- t5 From the Concept of Palingenesis to the Concept of Enlightenment -- t6 The Death of God and the Problem of Autonomy -- t7 The Idea of Autonomy and the Concept of Civil Society -- t8 From Romanticism to Classicism -- t9 The Return of Rome -- t10 Civil Society and the State -- t11 From Autonomy to Democracy -- t12 The Politics of Unsocial Sociability -- tAppendix: Lord Acton on the Romans, the Germans, and the Moderns -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTracing the origins of modern political thought through three sets of arguments over history, morality, and freedomIn this wide-ranging work, Michael Sonenscher traces the origins of modern political thought and ideologies to a question, raised by Immanuel Kant, about what is involved in comparing individual human lives to the whole of human history. How can we compare them, or understand the results of the comparison? Kant’s question injected a new, future-oriented dimension into existing discussions of prevailing norms, challenging their orientation toward the past. This reversal made Kant’s question a bridge between three successive sets of arguments: between the supporters of the ancients and moderns, the classics and romantics, and the Romans and the Germans. Sonenscher argues that the genealogy of modern political ideologies—from liberalism to nationalism to communism—can be connected to the resulting discussions of time, history, and values, mainly in France but also in Germany, Switzerland, and Britain, in the period straddling the French and Industrial revolutions.What is the genuinely human content of human history? Everything begins somewhere—democracy with the Greeks, or the idea of a res publica with the Romans—but these local arrangements have become vectors of values that are, apparently, universal. The intellectual upheaval that Sonenscher describes involved a struggle to close the gap, highlighted by Kant, between individual lives and human history. After Kant is an examination of that struggle’s enduring impact on the history and the historiography of political thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophyxHistory. 0aPolitical science-Philosophy-History. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAbstention.  aAlfred Rosenberg.  aAntinomy.  aBacteria.  aCareer.  aCastanopsis.  aCivil society.  aCollective memory.  aConcept.  aControversy.  aCosmopolitanism.  aCriticism.  aDoctrine.  aEssay.  aForms of government.  aFriedrich Schleiermacher.  aGeorg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel.  aGerman philosophy.  aGod is dead.  aHannah Arendt.  aHegelianism.  aHeinrich von Treitschke.  aHenry Hallam.  aHerder.  aIdeology.  aImmanuel Kant.  aImperative mandate (Ukraine).  aIndividualis